I've visited hundreds of different marine environments, but there are only a few sights that have truly left an indelible mark on my memory.
The first time I was struck by such a scene was about a decade ago, off the rugged coastline of South Africa.
Every June and July, countless sardines migrate northward, which we call the "sardine run."
Believe me, these fish have no choice but to do so.
Because there are packs of hungry, agile predators chasing after them.
For example, dolphins that hunt in groups separate a portion of the sardines from the school, corralling them into a ball.
The dolphins drive these sardines closer to the surface, then plunge into the school to feast, relishing this mobile smorgasbord.
Following closely behind are the sharks.
Most people would assume that sharks and dolphins are natural enemies, but during the sardine run, they coexist.
In fact, with the dolphins' assistance, the sharks enjoy an even more satisfying feast.
Without the dolphins herding them, the sardines struggle to form a tight ball, and sharks often swim right through the middle of the school, like a knife through a doughnut, sometimes ending up with just a bellyful of water.
I've had several close encounters with shark packs during the sardine run, and I know that they don't see me as a threat.
But I still get bumped and brushed by tails, just like the other guests at this raucous feast.
