During the stormy Southwest Monsoon season, manta rays that inhabit the atoll waters congregate near Hanifaru, a small island in Baa Atoll.
Swarms of tiny shrimp and crabs, most smaller than our pupils, form the primary diet of manta rays.
When these plankton are more scattered, manta rays typically feed alone, rolling continuously in the water like puppies chasing their own tails.
And when the plankton accumulate in greater numbers, the manta rays begin to form long feeding lines, connecting head to tail, with the tasty morsels missed by the leading manta ray being scooped up by its trailing companions.
As the plankton in the bay accumulate in greater numbers, the manta rays draw closer together in formation, employing this unique feeding technique, which we call the "tornado feeding method."
The manta rays stack up, forming a tight spiral that creates a vortex, trapping the plankton and directing it straight into the manta rays' enormous mouths.
Diving among hundreds of manta rays is a sight I will never forget.
When I first went to Hanifaru to take photos, the area was not yet protected, and the ecosystem was threatened by local development.
By working with non-governmental organizations like the Manta Trust, my photographs ultimately helped secure Hanifaru's designation as a marine protected area.
Fishermen from nearby islands used to hunt many manta rays, using their skin to make traditional drums.
And now, they have become the most staunch protectors of the manta rays, which generate over $8 million annually for the Maldives.
