Earlier this year, to fulfill a contract with National Geographic, I traveled to the Baja California Peninsula.
On the Pacific side of the peninsula's midsection lies San Ignacio Lagoon, a crucial breeding ground for gray whales.
Over the past century, this coastline was a massive slaughterhouse, with over 20,000 gray whales killed here, leaving only a few hundred survivors.
And now, the descendants of these gray whales push their calves to the surface to play, frolic, and even interact with us.
This species has made a remarkable recovery.
On the other side of the peninsula lies Cabo Pulmo, a tranquil little fishing village.
Decades of overfishing had once pushed this village to the brink of bankruptcy.
In 1995, the local fishermen convinced the government to designate these waters as a marine protected area.
What unfolded next could be described as nothing short of a miracle.
In 2005, just a decade after the protection measures were implemented, scientists found that the local fish populations had recovered to record-breaking levels.
